@NODE WHATIS "What Is ITimer?"

@{B}@{I}WHAT IS ITIMER? @{UB}@{UI}

ITimer is a simple program that lets you see how much time you have spent
on the internet. When it is started, it puts a window on your Workbench
desktop with the ITimer interface and starts ticking away.

ITimer will also work out your online charges for you so you know how much
you will have spent on Internet time!

I initally designed ITimer because I saw an internet timer in a shopping
catalogue that stuck to the top of the monitor,and it cost Ł10. I thought
"Why not write one? At least it won't cost me anything that way!". So
ITimer was created, basically from my tightfistedness!!

Anyway, since late '97, ITimer has been developed and updated to include
new features to make it even easier to use. ITimer is my first program that
I have made available to the public, and I'm rather proud of it and the
response it has generated!

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "Installation"

@{B}@{I}INSTALLATION @{UB}@{UI}

To install the program, simply drag the ITimer directory to where-ever
you want. You can directly unarchive future versions straight over the
old directory.

To run the program, run it from Workbench or from the CLI/Shell type:

                          RUN >NIL: ITimer <arguments>

Replace <arguments> with the commands outlined in @{"CLI Options" LINK CLI}

Please note, that to run the program, you must have Workbench 2.x or higher
as lower versions (1.x) do not contain the gadtools.library which ITimer
needs to run. ITimer does not make a check on the version of the OS, so
if you have OS 1.x, chances are your Amiga will crash. Remember: You have
been warned!

@ENDNODE

@NODE USAGE "Using ITimer"

@{B}@{I}USAGE @{UB}@{UI}

@{I}Display: @{UI}

When the program is started, the clock starts a-tickin'! The checkbox at
the bottom shows if the timer is active - A tick in it means it is, no
tick means it isn't.

Under this are two clocks. The one on the left is the time on the current
session since you last started ITimer. The right-hand clock shows the time
since the reset all feature was last used.

In the window's title bar, the cost of your online time is shown. As default,
ITimer uses dollars and cents ("$" and "c") to represent costs, although
using the startup options, this can be changed. 

The cost of your online time depends on the settings in the @{"prefs window" LINK PREFS}.
There you can change the cost of the time.

If you want to exit the program, click on the close window button. This will
make ITimer save the current timings to the file "ITimer.prefs" so the clock
starts at the correct time next time it is started. Alternatively, to exit
the program, you can start it a second time using the icon or a CLI command.
If this is done, ITimer will quit in the same way as if you had clicked the
close window gadget.

@{I}Buttons: @{UI}

Active Checkbox: With this, you can control the status of the program to
                 either Active or Inactive. Click the box to toggle the
                 status.

?              : This will display the program's About window. For technical
                 limitations, this will only work when the timer is Inactive

P              : This will open the @{"prefs window" LINK PREFS}. This gadget will
                 only work when the timer is Inactive for technical reasons

Now            : Resets the clock that shows the current session time

All            : Completely resets both clocks. This could be done, for
                 example, when you recieve your phone bill when you've
                 paid for your time on-line.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PREFS "Prefs Window"

@{B}@{I}PREFS WINDOW @{UB}@{UI}

The prefs window lets you control how ITimer costs your internet time. In
the window, there are three scroll bars, "$/hr", "c/hr" and "Free" and the
"Okay" button.

"$/hr" shows how many dollars (or pounds, francs, etc) your internet time
costs per hour. "c/hr" shows how many cents (or pence, centimes, etc) the
time costs you. To set the cost at, say $1.25 per hour (I hope no-one
really has to set it that high!), move the "$/hr" bar to 1 and the "c/hr"
bar to 25.

"Free" lets you tell ITimer how many free hours you get as some ISP's give
you, for example, ten hours free. ITimer then takes this into account when
it calculates your online charges.

(If your ISP doesn't charge you at all for your online time, your telephone
provider most likely will so check with them the cost per hour to your ISP).

When you have set them to the values you want, click on Okay. If you want to
cancel the changes, simply close the window with the close gadget in the top
left corner.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CLI "Startup Options"

@{B}@{I}STARTUP OPTIONS @{UB}@{UI}

ITimer can use startup options which can be invoked from Workbench or the
CLI.

If you wish to use the options when you launch ITimer from Workbench,
the options need to be entered as tooltypes: Select the ITimer icon and
choose the Information option from the Icons menu. Please note that for
the tooltypes to work, the icon must be called ITimer.info: If you do
not rename the program or its icon file after installing, then everything
will be okay.

If you use the CLI, then a command line approach is required eg:

                 @{I} ITimer INACTIVE RESET WHOLE=Ł @{UI}


INACTIVE          This will stop the timer from automatically counting
                  from the moment the program is started. Click on the
                  Active checkbox to start counting. Default is to
                  start immediately after loading.


RESET             This will reset both timers before commencing. Same as
                  pressing the NOW button.


WHOLE=            This will let you choose the symbol which ITimer uses to
                  represent whole monetary values. The default is "$".
                  For example, to change the symbol to a pound sign use

                 @{I} WHOLE=Ł @{UI}


FRACTION=         This will let you choose the symbol which ITimer uses to
                  represent fractional monetary values. The default is
                  "c". For example, to change the symbol to the pence
                  sign use:

                 @{I} FRACTION=p @{UI}


ALARM=            This will set the time for the alarm. The time taken is
                  from the current session clock. The format of the
                  number after the word ALARM= is @{I}hhmmss@{UI}. For example:

                 @{I} ALARM=000030 @{UI} - Alarm set for 30 seconds
                 @{I} ALARM=003000 @{UI} - Alarm set for 30 minutes
                 @{I} ALARM=300000 @{UI} - Alarm set for 30 hours


ALARMTEXT=        In the requester which comes up as the alarm, you can place
                  the text of your choosing. If ALARMTEXT isn't set, a default
                  message is shown. Please note, due to AmigaDOS limitations,
                  messages with spaces cannot be done if you start ITimer from
                  the Shell/CLI.


AUTOSAVE=         This will make ITimer automatically save the prefs file
                  at the interval specified. A value of zero (0) will
                  turn off the autosave feature. This has been included as
                  sometimes, if your Amiga crashes before ITimer is exited,
                  the new timings wouldn't be saved. For example:

                 @{I} AUTOSAVE=120 @{UI}

                  This would make the program save the prefs every 120
                  seconds (two minutes). Please note the timer routine
                  for this isn't entirely accurate (ie it may save a few
                  seconds before or after it should) but it will work
                  as it should apart from this.


PREFSDIR=         This will let you specify the directory in which the
                  ITimer.prefs file is saved to. The directory must exist.
                  The default is ENVARC:   EG: To save the prefs file in
                  the Work:Progs/ITimer/ directory, type the following:

                 @{I} PREFSDIR=Work:Progs/ITimer/ @{UI}

                  Please note that the last character MUST be either a
                  ":" or a "/"


WINDOWX=          This allows you to set the "X" (horizontal) position of
                  the window on the screen. Type the position (in pixels)
                  after the option. For example:

                 @{I} WINDOWX=200 @{UI}


WINDOWY=          As WINDOWX but alters the "Y" (vertical) position of the
                  window.

                  *NB*: The settings in WINDOWX and WINDOWY will override the
                  window's snapshot position in the prefs file.


NOSNAPSHOT        Normally, when ITimer is exited, the window position will
                  also be saved in the prefs file. Using this option will
                  prevent ITimer from doing this.


NOSAVE            This will stop the program from saving the prefs file which
                  contains the time data, etc. However, the previous prefs
                  file will remain (ITimer.prefs)


DEBUG             This is really for development use only, but I left it in
                  in case users felt they needed it. Instead of loading and
                  saving data in the "ITimer.prefs" file, using the
                  DEBUG command makes the program use the
                  "ITimer.prefs.TEST" file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TIPS "Tips 'n' Tricks"

@{B}@{I}TIPS 'N' TRICKS @{UB}@{UI}

· Although ITimer cannot yet automatically activate or de-activate when
  you connect/disconnect your modem, there is a way of getting it to
  start when you log-in to your internet provider: If you use AmiTCP, then
  you can change your Run or Connect script to include the lines:

                    RUN >NIL: ITimer <arguments>

  This will make ITimer start when you run your login script. Replace
  <arguments> with the CLI commands outlined in @{"CLI Options" LINK CLI}

  A similar effect can be achieved by running other TCP stacks (eg Termite
  TCP or Miami) via an AmigaDOS script rather than through an icon.

· Before you use Reset, make the timer inactive then click Reset. This
  helps if you don't want it to start counting again straight away.

· If you want to keep a record of a month's online time, for example, then
  before running ITimer and resetting it, rename the ITimer.prefs file to
  something like NOV97.ITimer.prefs

@ENDNODE

